---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Privacy Policy | Running Coach"
  description="A short, plain-language privacy page for Running Coach."
  pathname="/privacy"
>
  <article class="shell privacy-page">
    <header class="privacy-hero">
      <div class="privacy-hero__intro privacy-motion privacy-motion--1">
        <p class="eyebrow">Privacy</p>
        <h1>Privacy, explained without the legal maze.</h1>
        <p class="lede privacy-hero__lede">
          A plain-language view of what Running Coach uses, why it uses it, and how
          early-access requests are handled.
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside class="privacy-summary privacy-motion privacy-motion--2" aria-labelledby="privacy-summary-title">
        <p class="eyebrow">In short</p>
        <h2 id="privacy-summary-title">What users should expect right now.</h2>
        <div class="privacy-summary__stack">
          <section class="privacy-summary__item" aria-labelledby="privacy-summary-data">
            <h3 id="privacy-summary-data">Only relevant data</h3>
            <p>Used to keep the service working and weekly planning believable.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="privacy-summary__item" aria-labelledby="privacy-summary-provider">
            <h3 id="privacy-summary-provider">Intervals provider</h3>
            <p>Intervals is the current source for athlete-specific data ingestion.</p>
          </section>

          <section class="privacy-summary__item" aria-labelledby="privacy-summary-requests">
            <h3 id="privacy-summary-requests">Deletion or disconnect</h3>
            <p>The same support route is used for privacy-related requests during early access.</p>
          </section>
        </div>
      </aside>
    </header>

    <div class="privacy-layout">
      <div class="privacy-content">
        <section class="privacy-section privacy-section--lead privacy-motion privacy-motion--2">
          <p class="eyebrow">Scope</p>
          <h2>Who this applies to</h2>
          <p>
            This policy applies to people who use the Running Coach website, connect a
            training account, or receive weekly planning through the portal.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="privacy-duo privacy-motion privacy-motion--3" aria-label="Data use details">
          <article class="privacy-card">
            <p class="eyebrow">Data use</p>
            <h2>What data may be used</h2>
            <p>
              Running Coach may use account details, recent activity history, training
              metrics, and connection details needed to keep linked services working and to
              generate weekly guidance.
            </p>
          </article>

          <article class="privacy-card privacy-card--soft">
            <p class="eyebrow">Reason</p>
            <h2>Why it is used</h2>
            <p>
              The point is to understand recent training, generate a more believable
              weekly plan, maintain connected integrations, and support early users when
              something goes wrong.
            </p>
          </article>
        </section>

        <section class="privacy-callout privacy-motion privacy-motion--3">
          <p class="eyebrow">Providers and retention</p>
          <h2>Connected services should only support the product, not complicate it.</h2>
          <p>
            Running Coach currently relies on Intervals for athlete-specific data
            ingestion. Data should only be kept for as long as it is needed to operate the
            service, support users, and meet legal obligations.
          </p>
        </section>

        <footer class="privacy-footer privacy-motion privacy-motion--4">
          <div class="privacy-support">
            <p class="eyebrow">Support</p>
            <h2>Need a deletion or disconnection request?</h2>
            <p>
              During early access, onboarding, support, deletion, and disconnection
              requests all use the same simple route.
            </p>
          </div>
          <aside class="privacy-meta" aria-label="Privacy page notes">
            <div class="privacy-meta__item">
              <p class="eyebrow">Current release</p>
              <p>Early-access web release.</p>
            </div>
            <p class="privacy-meta__note">
              Written in plain language instead of acting like legal filler.
            </p>
          </aside>
        </footer>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
